title: For Sale:  Custom Gen 4 Glock 17 w/ EXTRAS!
postcontent:
Hi there, I have cut back on shooting quite a bit and had been setting this gun up for USPSA Open division. It's literally all done out minus the cmore slide ride that i had plans to put on it.

This is a gen 4 Glock 17 purchased roughly 5 months ago. Round count is relatively low. I would estimate around 3k rounds down the tube. This gun is an absolute dream to shoot. I set it up with the intention to make this gun the best it could possibly be.

This is a list of the modifications and i'll put the price i paid for each part to give you a better idea of how much actually went into the gun.

Gen 4 Glock 17- $550

10#, 11#, 12# 17# Recoil springs (all included) -$30
Dawson Ext basepad - $35
Plus case, hearing, and eye protection and ammo, we'll just round way down and say $50.
The point is there is well over $1000 extra dollars worth of add ons, but i'm going to be realistic and understand that i'm obviously not going to get that money back, i would just like the buyer to see how much actually went into this pistol.

The gun includes 4 mags total. It will come with three stock 17 round mags and one more mag with a extended Dawson Precision base pad allowing the mag to hold around 24 rounds.

I'm also included the case shown in the picture, eye protection, hearing protection, and i have about 50 rounds of misc. 9mm jacketed hollowpoints. I will include all of the original parts except for the stock barrel. I no longer have that.

There were a few modifications made to the gun to make it a little more ergonomic and fit the hand better. The trigger guard has a double undercut on it so you can get your hand up higher for more control. The finger grooves were taken off and the grip has a grip tape wrap. This allows for a much more solid and comfortable shooting grip.

If you have any questions please feel free to text me at REDACTED.

INFORMATION FROM WIKIPEDIA When the LWRC Six8 was being developed, Alliant Techsystems was contracted to develop a new 6.8x43mm round for the weapon. Unlike smaller commercial firms, ATK is a large ammunition supplier that delivers products for the U.S. Army, so it had large resources and manufacturing capabilities at its disposal. Commercial cartridges varied in case capacity and thickness, but LWRC wanted a thick and durable case for military uses. A 90 gr (5.8 g) load was developed specifically for a high muzzle velocity and low felt recoil from the Six8's 8.5 in (220 mm) barrel. Effective range would be over 300 yd (274 m) and the bullet would still have enough energy to penetrate intermediate barriers. Three 90 gr loads were constructed for testing that included Gold Dot, Monolithic Hollow Point, and FMJ. The Gold Dot bullet was selected with a .035 in (0.89 mm) jacket and a bonded core. The propellant was designed for reduced muzzle flash stable performance at temperatures between -29.2 to 125.6 degrees F. Muzzle velocity averaged at a 200 ft/s (61 m/s) difference at the required temperature extremes from the 8.5 in barrel. title: For Sale:  Ruger m77 .25-06 (1988 model)
location: Hartford. KS (hour south ot Topeka), Topeka, Kansas
postcontent:
This is my dad's old rifle I haven't been shooting enough to keep.  I was going to reload for it and I bought a LOT of brass, bullets last year... but I'm giving up and so I'm selling it all off here:  

http://www.armslist.com/posts/2882913/topeka-kansas-ammo-for-sale--25-06-brass--dies--bullets-and-cartridges--and-offer-with-rifle-

This rifle has killed about 20 deer and 20 more hogs and it rarely was shot more than once for the kill.  90% of the ammo shot through it was dad's reloads (which he ran a few before deer season down the barrel to check the zero).  Dad had some bench shooters and bigger rifles-- but this rifle was used for hunting.  I got it 18 years ago and haven't gone through two factory boxes since then (there are 6 bullets left out of box #2 bought in about 1999).

I later bought the extra cases and bullets (last few years) but never got to loading it and so just to say-- this rifle has had about 200 bullets down it it's entire life (and this is important to know when buying a used gun)  Although this rifle is a great varmint rifle to some, this rifle was only used to feed the family and shoot an occasional coyote (or politician's sign out in the pasture) every so often.

I have some very close-up, detailed pictures I'd send a sincere buyer and they will show light wear in all the places a 26 year old gun should have it.  The barrel and action are super clean with no scratches the camera can catch (and there is one "spot" the size of a pin's head right under the barrel forward of the stock about an inch) otherwise it would be called "near mint" by some.  The scope rings have some wear on the edges, the bolt has a shiny spot on the tip of the ball (again, the camera can't see it but I have a pic to show what I can).  The scope caps have the most noticeable wear (the scope is older than the rifle-- about 40 years old-- so more wear).  While the scope body is still pretty clean, there is a spot or two showing wear close-up (again I have pictures).  There are a few light scratches in the stock, but nothing more.

The scope is a 4x32, "Valor" scope form the 70s which has been on it since the rifle was bought.  Dad took it from an older gun and put it on this Ruger when he bought it new in 1989 (from "MadDog's Gunshop" in Roswell, NM).  The Valor scope is a long gone brand, but is a decent (Japanese made) scope with good glass and last January 2013, I shot a deer, in 5 degrees at early dusk, and it didn't fog.  It has an "old school", thin haired reticle (picture available).

I'd take $800 (obo) for the rifle and this INCLUDES about $350 in reloading dies, bullets, cases, etc.  I don't have the press, powder or anything else left for sale except for what is listed above.  The Rifle by itself can sell for $550 (obo).  I'd prefer a face-to-face meeting for cash in East Kansas (on a weekend I could get get away your direction) if 30 miles or further away from Hartford, KS (near Emporia).  But I'd sell it mailed for shipping and FFL fees to any legal US state (in the 48 states) but it will take time as I live in the country and go to town a few times a week-- so no rush jobs please.

Sincere offers will each be responded to and if I sell off the reloading items, I'll update this listing.  But please send a name and number to receive the same in kind; as I won't be able to reply to anyone less than sincere.  Thank you.

First off these weapons were captured by the Soviets on the Eastern Front and every one taken forcefully from the German military. THESE are the weapons an invader would have faced from the Soviet Homeguard had such a war occured. There are dies for 45acp, 45 Colt, about 6 or so for .38/.357, and .30 Carbine.  There are a dozen or so locking rings, an extra round nose and SWC seating head for .38, and some other nuts and bolts.  The boxes for the dies were damaged and covered in oil so I threw them out. Everything goes together as a lot.
